AGI -&nbsp;The al-Shifa hospital in Gaza City, > the largest of the entire Strip, is "completely out of service >" after two weeks of military operations > by the Israeli army in the area and its surroundings. "The destruction of the complex makes it impossible to resume the work and the hospital is completely out of service," said the structure manager, Marwan Abu Saada. The Israeli forces insist that their military operations were not directed against "patients, health personnel or medical equipment", although the Gaza Ministry of Health, controlled by Hamas, > reported that the raids caused the death of at least 400 people.> "We ask the international community, first, to investigate what happened in the medical complex and, secondly, to seek alternatives to the health services provided," said the director of Shifa.
&nbsp;
The widespread images of the hospital after the withdrawal of the Israeli forces show a wide trail of destruction throughout the area, with destroyed buildings and much of the medical complex carbonized by the intense fire resulting from the attacks lasted two weeks. The Civil Protection of the Gaza Strip reported that, after the withdrawal of Israeli troops from the Shifa hospital, bodies were found with execution signs, other burned> and even in decomposition state. &nbsp;>
<h2> The US will ask for explanations</h2>
The tanks and vehicles of the Israeli army left the hospital complex where they had entered two weeks ago. According to an Afp journalist, the army shot grenades to cover the withdrawal of heavy vehicles and moved away from the Al-Rimal district to head south-west of Gaza City, to the Tel al-Hawa district. The White House will ask Israel "more information" about the bodies found in the hospital, announced spokesman Karine Jean-Pierre in the usual briefing with the press.
&nbsp;
"It is very worrying if it is true," said Jean-Pierre, adding that Washington "will meet the Israeli government for more information." Doctors and civilians in the hospital complex reported to the media that were found in the structure at least 20 bodies, some of which seem to have been invested by military vehicles. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
In the meantime, the surgery to which the Israeli Prime Minister was subjected is "reuscised". Benjamin Netanyahu> is "in good shape and is beginning to recover", said his office at the end of the operation, followed closely in Israel and abroad.
<h2> The hospital of Al-Aqsa</h2>
The head of the Oms, Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus>, then denounced that in an Israeli air attack carried out against another hospital in Gaza, that of Al-Aqsa, four people died and another 17 were wounded. The raid at the hospital was testified by a team of the World Health Organization sent to the place to assess needs and collect incubators for the north of Gaza, said Tedros in a post on X. The Israeli army denied that the hospital was damaged. "A team of the Oms was on humanitarian mission at the Al-Aqsa hospital in Gaza, when a tendopolis inside the hospital complex was struck on Sunday, March 31 by an Israeli air strike," wrote the head of the Oms, who did not provide details about the victims.
&nbsp;
On the other hand, the Israeli army replicated X that one of its aircraft "has hit an operating center of Islamic Jihad and terrorists located in the courtyard of the Al-Aqsa hospital in the Deir al Balah area. "As a result of the impact, the Al-Aqsa hospital building was not damaged and its function was not compromised," he added. Tedros has renewed his appeal for patients, health workers and humanitarian workers to be protected during the conflict and to prevent attacks on hospitals. "The ongoing attacks and militarization of hospitals must end - he added -. International humanitarian law must be respected." Tedros urged all parties in conflict to respect the UN Security Council resolution calling for a ceasefire.&nbsp;

